50|$|On June 20, 1934 the Farmers and Merchants Bank {{was robbed}} {{by a group}} of men. The group took 13 <b>hostages</b> to help conceal the attempt and to help move the safe. They had the <b>hostages</b> load the safe {{into the back of a}} truck and drove the <b>hostages</b> and safe out of town. They ended up leaving both behind, <b>hostages</b> unhurt and safe unopened.|$|R
25|$|The {{bodies of}} dead <b>hostages</b> {{were put in}} two buses which were parked at the TC. Initial reports said nothing about {{casualties}} among the <b>hostages.</b> The crisis HQ representatives went to the college hall, where relatives of the <b>hostages</b> had been waiting, {{and told them that}} allegedly there were no fatalities among the <b>hostages.</b> The first official report of fatalities among the <b>hostages</b> came at about 9:00a.m. (despite the death of five children which had been already reported by medical personnel, the official statement claimed there were no children among the dead).|$|R
